Add aggregates endpoint

This patch adds a new `aggregates` endpoint that retrieves the
missioncontrol data from presto provided a list of dimensions, measurements and conditions.
This is done using an instance of QueryBuilder, which holds the logic
to create a sqlalchemy selectable object and runs the query. This is
the first iteration so it's limited in functionalities. At the moment
it's not possible to:
 - filter by a non-exact match
 - filter by a time range
 - use a custom temporal resolution

Use a variant of alphanumeric version sorting in release summary view (#263)

This is what we actually want, given that we are sorting a list that
normally includes a summary of each release number ('60') and *one*
specific beta/alpha/point release which is the latest ('59.0.3')

Fix version sorting (#262)

* Use version-sort instead of compare-versions (it actually works for our
  weird version numbers like `58.0b3`)
* Sort version data in the detail view (fixes #239)

Allow showing aggregated data on 5 minute / 1 hour / daily intervals (#150)

Defaulting to 1 hour, which seems to work pretty well for most views. This
makes the graphs easier to read, and solves most of the slowness issues
that people have been experiencing (e.g. in #199)
Fix version sorting in relative release view for reals (#261)
Speed up relative release api endpoint (#260) (fixes #258)

Fix versions returned by relative release view in beta (#259)

In the case of beta, we need to use version sort, not lexographic
sort (just as we do elsewhere in mission control).

Adjust measure summary calculation somewhat (#257)

Instead of taking the mean of the rate (which might include some entries with
very low usage hours), take the sum of errors and divide it by the sum of
usage hours. Use only the 99th percentile of rate results, to remove weird
outlier aggregates.

Handle large beta numbers when querying / displaying data (#256)

Version strings like 55.0b10 will come before 55.0b9 lexographically,
we need to modify our sql and presto queries accordingly.

Specify which channels a measure applies to (fixes #218) (#255)

Most quality measures (e.g. slow script counts) are only applicable to
the pre-release channels, so let's not show them on the release dashboard.

Show values that are at the percentile in detail view (#254)

Only showing those below the percentile threshold could cause errors
if there are a low number of non-zero datapoints.

Fix monkeypatching our presto raw_query method

The new experiments etl caused the method that queries presto to be
imported earlier in the unit test process, which made it impossible to
monkeypatch. Hack around this in the source itself by importing the
query function where it's used instead. Not especially happy with this
solution, I suspect we ought to rework the presto/athena integration
code somehow to make testing easier.

Remove doc placeholders (#187)

We had placeholders for generating a full set of documentation via sphinx,
but this approach is overkill for the project in its current state. Let's
just use some simple markdown documents for now, can always do something
bigger/better in the future if it is warranted.

Make measure summary more meaningful (#186)

Instead of giving a median of the previous version's counts at the present
time (which is quite biased), calculate the previous version's counts at the
same time as the present one. This helps account for skew as people first
start to update to a previous version.

Also add standard deviation to the API endpoint and web-based summary (to give
at least a superficial idea of whether the current/previous results are
comparable)

Replace tox with raw calls to pytest (#185)

tox has a really long setup cycle, and we don't really need its functionality
for testing missioncontrol (which is a web application running in a deterministic
environment)

Refactor date selector into its own component (#173)

Don't update graphs unnecessarily in detail view (#172)

We were previously updating the measure/time graphs in the detail view
every time any aspect of the global state changed, even when such a
state did not effect the graphs at all (e.g. the user was just changing
the time picker). This operation could be extremely slow when we're
visualizing a large amount of data. Use react's shouldComponentUpdate
functionality to avoid unnecessary updates.
